Here's how to make your page theme-aware:

## XAML — `AppThemeBinding`

Replace every hardcoded color with `AppThemeBinding`, which automatically picks the right value based on the OS theme:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=#1E1E1E}">

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="15">

        <Label Text="Welcome"
               FontSize="24"
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#333333, Dark=#F0F0F0}" />

        <Label Text="This page responds to system theme."
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#666666, Dark=#CCCCCC}" />

        <Button Text="Get Started"
                BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#2196F3, Dark=#BB86FC}"
                TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=Black}" />

    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

No code-behind changes needed — the OS theme drives everything automatically.

## C# Alternative — `SetAppThemeColor`

If you build UI in code, use the extension methods:

```csharp
var page = new ContentPage();
page.SetAppThemeColor(ContentPage.BackgroundColorProperty, Colors.White, Color.FromArgb("#1E1E1E"));

var title = new Label { Text = "Welcome", FontSize = 24 };
title.SetAppThemeColor(Label.TextColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#333333"), Color.FromArgb("#F0F0F0"));

var button = new Button { Text = "Get Started" };
button.SetAppThemeColor(Button.BackgroundColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#2196F3"), Color.FromArgb("#BB86FC"));
button.SetAppThemeColor(Button.TextColorProperty, Colors.White, Colors.Black);
```

For non-color properties, use the generic form:

```csharp
label.SetAppTheme<string>(Label.TextProperty, "Light Mode", "Dark Mode");
```

## Key things to know

1. **Android requirement** — ensure `MainActivity` includes `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or theme changes trigger a full activity restart instead of a smooth switch.

2. **Detect/override theme in code** if needed:
   ```csharp
   // Read current theme
   AppTheme current = Application.Current!.RequestedTheme;

   // Force dark regardless of OS
   Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

   // Follow OS again
   Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
   ```

3. **React to changes** at runtime:
   ```csharp
   Application.Current!.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
   {
       // e.RequestedTheme is the new theme
   };
   ```

`AppThemeBinding` is the simplest approach for OS-driven light/dark. If you later need more than two themes or custom brand palettes, switch to **ResourceDictionary swapping** with `DynamicResource` bindings.
